$E(2001,501)=5$. First, note that three minutes is not enough time to flip each switch once. In four minutes, Elizabeth can flip each switch once, but has three flips left over. Because there are an odd number of leftover flips to distribute among the 2001 switches, some switch must get an odd number of leftover flips, and thus an even number of total flips. Thus $E(2001,501)>4$.

To solve the puzzle in five minutes, Elizabeth can flip the following sets of switches:

- in the first minute, $\{1,2,3, \ldots, 501\}$;
- in the second minute, $\{1,2,3, \ldots, 102\}$ and $\{502,503,504, \ldots, 900\}$;
- in the third minute, $\{1,2,3, \ldots, 102\}$ and $\{901,902,903, \ldots, 1299\}$;
- in the fourth minute, $\{1,2,3, \ldots, 100\}$ and $\{1300,1301,1302, \ldots, 1700\}$;
- in the fifth minute, $\{1,2,3, \ldots, 100\}$ and $\{1701,1702,1703, \ldots, 2001\}$.

This results in switches $1,2,3, \ldots, 100$ being flipped five times, switches 101 and 102 being flipped three times, and the remaining switches being flipped exactly once, so that all the lights are on at the end of the fifth minute.

In simplifying the numerator and denominator of the left side of the equation, notice that

$$
\begin{aligned}
k+(k+1)+\cdots+k n & =\frac{1}{2}(k n(k n+1)-k(k-1)) \\
& =\frac{1}{2}(k(n+1)(k n-k+1))
\end{aligned}
$$

This identity allows the given equation to be transformed:

$$
